Remarks: The size of the femoral teeth is somewhat variable and therefore Schuster (1916) listed in his identification key this species under two alternatives. In the same group belongs
L. osmanlis Reitter, 1906
, but this species has a complete different apicale of the aedeagus (compare Figs. 43, 46 ). Most of the available males from Turkey and also from the adjacent Greek islands bear a tiny tooth on the inner side of the posterior tibia ( Fig. 24 ). New record for Greece (probably restricted to the Greek islands adjacent of the Turkish western coast).
Published localities: Konstantinopel, Alem Dagh, Goek Dagh, Sabandja, Smyrna ( Schuster 1916 ). Ulu Dagh ( Ferrer & Soldati 1999 ).
